The man, old and rich, crossed the doors of the customer service center of the RPG Byty company of the "coal magnate" Zdeęek Bakala, the largest private owner of apartments for rent in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm he was carrying documents with the new three-storey rental contracts: his, his daughter's, and his son's, who is serving sentence.
The three of them have just been caught by the liberalization of rents.
Instead of 3,500 Czech crowns per month, the child will pay from next year 4,100 crowns for a two-bedroom floor with separate second-category kitchen.
"In addition, it does not have hot water and heating is based on a solid fuel boiler," the man shows with his finger in his son's new contract, on whose signature he has full powers.
"But I signed it," explains half angry, half resigned.
