Architects have understood that offices also need nursery
The administrative building Avriopoint in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
No one would say that he also hides inside a small nursery with everything that is proper to such facilities: colored walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, the children of Arch.Design employees can come to her.
The architectural project company Arch.Design, from whose study numerous well-known buildings emerged from Brno, thought from the first sketches of the Avriopoint building to include a space for its minigarde.
The company employs about 90 people, mainly at the age of baby boom and wanted to allow architects and delineants to return to work soon after maternity.
Together with the possibility of enjoying a reduced schedule, childcare is one of the benefits offered by Arch.Design to your workers within the framework of your social program.
Constructors and architects thus have the possibility of combining a demanding profession with the care of children.
The minigarde was an idea of Arch.Designu's own employees and, with the support of the leadership, they managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company's mini-guards are financed through the European Social Fund under the Human Resources and Employment Operation Programme as well as the State budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the funding granted (a budget of more than 2.8 million Czech krona) they were able to purchase the equipment and, after two years, to hire qualified personnel and services.
When the funding is exhausted (two years), Arch.Design has an obligation to keep the mini-garde in operation with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and in the submission of the application for funding the company Economy Rating contributed.
The care of children is in the hands of qualified personnel; in addition, a nurse and a teacher from the Ministry of Education are present all day long; the childcare centre currently accommodates children without a limit of age, although most of them are under three years old.
Since it is a "mini-guard care" it can only accommodate a maximum of five children simultaneously, although with the shifts they come more during the day.
The operation of childcare is flexible to adapt to the needs of parents and children of all workers have the same right to use childcare, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although it is individual education and care, the contents of the minigarde programme are comparable to the usual pre-school education programme.
In it children not only play, but also receive quality education: from basic learning to school preparation, they teach to English.
The class has not only toys and table games, but also a computer for children.
The presence of young children in the company itself creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can go to see their children at any time and avoid stress from collecting late school children when they are away from their place of work.
Thus, parents are more productive while working.
It is not surprising that this naturally generates a relationship of loyalty between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design is located among companies that offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, ultimately, this program strengthened the marketing of staff.
The house of bones continues to fascinate after 100 years.
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs remind the column of a dinosaur and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batlló, in Barcelona, by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Due to its similar form to a skeleton, the locals nicknamed it "the house of the bones".
Its organic forms, its striking colors, the innovative use of the stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a façade that reminds the scales and the omnipresent softly curved lines, all this is typical of the secession of Antoni Gaudí.
The cover of the house plays with onyric lines, delicate colors and textures drawn from nature and fauna.
With more attention, a certain geometry, rhythm and carefully thought order are observed.
At night, the whole facade of the house seems even more impressive, as it is illuminated in such a way that the brightness of the colors is improved.
Serpentea and the torsion of the shapes continue to surprise us also inside it.
The undulated wood copies the frames of the windows, the bars, the ornaments of the doors, the mills and the signs.
The Casa Batlló, which is located in the Eixample neighborhood on the 43th of the lively shopping street of Passeig de Grácia, emerged from the refurbishment of a house of 1877 by architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the rich industrial Josep Batlló, initially insisted on demolishing the previous building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaudí's idea of carrying out a new and cheaper reconstruction.
However, the Casa Batlló, made up of various apartments, did not design it alone Antoni Gaudí.
The architect Josep María Jujol collaborated in the design.
In fact, in his plans of the project emerged ornaments for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the mosaics used on the façade.
On the façade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration in the proposals of the Casa Batlló was the beginning of Jujol's successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of the Casa Milá and the Güell de Gaudí park, where other parts of it are found.
Due to its organic form, the premises shortly after their completion nicknamed it "the house of the bones".
Others, because of the specific window opening mechanism, began to call it "the house of the moanings".
It is also said that, at the top of the construction, the sword of Saint George, patron of Catalonia appears.
Other sculpture elements of the construction hide religious motives.
Gaudí projected in the house a unique system for the central heating time with ventilation vents and typical fireplaces.
It may be strange your inclination of forty-five degrees.
During the construction, Gaudí did not respect at all the construction rules of the moment and was not allowed to influence by them.
However, the construction obtained the corresponding permit from the beginning, although clearly in it the data indicated on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, at the end of the construction, the town hall was so impacted with the result that it requested that it be corrected.
He was disturbed, for example, that the construction included columns even to the public sidewalk.
The arrangements were never made, on the contrary: only fifteen days after the City Council's request, Josep Batlló requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
The owner himself was installed on the lower floors.
On the second floor gallery was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The six-storey house is completely crossed by a staircase that leads to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted of breaking all the angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of space connection.
The common part can be connected completely by opening the doors of the halls and a larger group can communicate in this way without problems, without giving up the privacy necessary for more intimate conversations.
The house, with the reconstruction of Gaudí, not only got a new façade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with light, white and blue tiles that cover the inner courtyard and slots.
The game with the two colors gives the maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was simply based on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which on the contrary absorb sunlights.
Anyone can visit the Casa Batlló, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house you will find the most spacious and more recharged apartment of those accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that this is a very beneficial business and extended the visits to the common area and the buhardilla, including the roof terrace.
The price of entry to the monument is not negligible, it reaches 16.50 euros, although students, retirees and tourist card holders get a 20% discount.
The amount exceeds considerably the price of the entry of other buildings of Gaudí in the city.
