A longer index finger than annulment indicates a lower risk of cancer
Men who have the longest index than annulment are subject to a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday in a British magazine on cancer.
It could depend on the testosterone level, the male hormone.
"Our results indicate that relative finger length can be a simple test of the risk of prostate cancer, particularly for men up to 60 years of age," said the co-author of the study Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at Warwick University.
Therefore, the finger could help determine which men should undergo a prostate cancer test, in particular if this characteristic is associated with a genetic risk or other harmful factors, such as family health problems, as Eeles indicates.
During the period 1994-2009, he followed up with a British counterpart of over 1,500 patients with prostate cancer and, simultaneously, 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had the finger of the right hand shorter than the annulment.
They presented the same probability of prostate cancer as 19% of those whose fingers were of the same length.
In the case of men with a longer index than annulment finger, this risk was reduced by 33%; for men with ages below 60%, the reduction reached 87%.
The relationship between the length of the two fingers in question, determined in the prenatal period, reflects different levels of hormones to which the fetus is exposed in the matrix.
A lower testosterone level corresponds to a longer index.
Previous studies indicated that testosterone influences the development of prostate cancer.
The great Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, Professor Václav Pačes, told ČTK that he knows the study, but that it does not seem that the relationship between the length of the fingers and the cancer can be "demonstrated completely".
