Support for democracy in Latin America continues to increase, as well as support for private companies.
Crime caused greater concern than unemployment.
In addition, in most parts of the region, Brazil is seen as a more influential country than the United States.
These are some of the conclusions of the last Latinobarometer survey conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
Since the survey has been held regularly since 1995, it enables monitoring of changes in attitudes in the region.
Two related issues are highlighted in the results of this year's survey in September and early October.
The first is the relatively lively mood reigning in Latin America.
The second is the growing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has increased considerably in various countries on the Pacific coast of South America (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has reached an average of 6 per cent annually since 2002, support for democracy has increased from 40 per cent in 2005 to 61 per cent this year.
It also grew in Mexico, where the economy has recovered after a major decline in production last year.
However, only half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populated countries in the area, are convinced democrats, which lowers the regional average (see figure 2).
About 44 per cent of respondents in the region were satisfied with the way democracy works in practice in their country, the same number as last year, but significantly more than 25 per cent in 2001 (figure 3).
About 34 per cent said that they trusted the Congress of their country and 45 per cent in their Government, the same amount as last year in both cases, but considerably higher than 2003 (17 per cent and 24 per cent, respectively).
A decade ago, economic turbulence in Latin America severely affected support for democracy.
The fact that it had remained during the global financial crisis was probably due to the fact that many Latin American countries were only affected by a short recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, the existence of a stronger social security network has contributed to protecting the poorest.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty increased only marginally in 2009 and has declined again this year, to 32 per cent.)
However, the mood varies considerably from one country to another (see figure 4).
Brazil's good economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, are reflected in a general sense of progress.
Such a feeling is less common in Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more serious and violent crimes have increased.
For the second time since the surveys began, more respondents in Latin America mention crime, rather than unemployment, as the most serious problem facing their country (see figure 5).
About 31 per cent say that either they or a close relative has been the victim of crime in the past year, a figure that has been reduced since 38 per cent last year and is the lowest percentage since 1995.
The most positive economic performance is reflected in increased support for private enterprises and the market economy: around 71 per cent of respondents in the region claim that private enterprises are indispensable for development, while in 2007 it was only 56 per cent (see figure 6).
About 58% agree that the market economy is the only system that will allow your country to develop, compared to 47% last year.
It is interesting that 62% of Venezuela's respondents feel the same (and 80% support private companies), although their left-wing president Hugo Chávez is expropriating numerous private companies.
Brazil is the country that has the highest leadership in the region, as 19% of respondents (compared to 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, same as last year) and Venezuela (9% versus 11% a year ago).
However, the United States is considered the country most influential by those surveyed in Mexico and much of Central America, while Venezuela holds such a title in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
