Cockell wasn't part of the investigation team.
"This work is innovative because it demonstrates the replacement of one element by the other in biochemistry and the basic biochemistry structure," Cockell added.
The discovery was not done by chance.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of the NASA astrobiology institute, who led the study, focused on the Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are similar from the chemical point of view, so it speculated that a microbe exposed to both could replace each other.
"Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is similar to that of phosphorus."
"Therefore, it may be difficult for the organisms to differentiate them."
"However, the arsenic is different enough to not work as well as the phosphorus, so it enters and, to say it somehow, appeals to the biochemical machinery," explains Anbar.
Researchers collected the bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed them to increasing arsenic concentrations, which they managed to adapt and use to grow.
The microbi grows better with phosphorus, but the fact that it can prove that it can live with arsenic instead poses the possibility that there may naturally be a way of life that uses arsenic, either in other areas of the Earth or on another planet or moon where the arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, an assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, indicated that the idea that arsenic can be replaced by phosphorus is not new, but an example has never been found to prove that it works.
The arsenic was more common in the early eras of the Earth, he pointed out, so researchers speculated that the first forms of life could have used it.
"Yes, it suggests that there could be other means of generating life, not only the way life was formed on Earth anciently," said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
