Prosecutors will not raise charges against Senator Ensign.
Senator's lawyers announced on Wednesday that the prosecutors of the Department of Justice have expelled Senator John Ensign from the criminal charges that emerged from his affair with a former campaign assistant and his efforts to secure work through lobby for the wife's husband.
The decision ends with the most serious legal threat facing Ensign, the Republican of Nevada who was considered a possible Republican presidential candidate by 2012, until the scandal about his affair had national holders last year and damaged his career.
Ensign's office said he felt "certainly happy" for the decision, which came after an entire year's investigation.
The senator could still face a disciplinary measure of the Senate ethics committee.
Ensign's lawyers said that the Department of Justice had "informed us that Senator Ensign is no longer an objective of his investigation and that he has no plan to raise charges against him on this subject."
The Department of Justice did not wish to comment on the case.
The announcement was a surprise for many ethics lawyers outside the Department of Justice, who said there seemed to be significant evidence to indicate that Ensign could have plotted to violate a federal criminal ban on lobby.
The interviews, emails and other documents that were first released in October 2009 at the New York Times indicated that Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, to obtain lucrative work through lobby, to achieve the silence of Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the Senator's affair with her.
Mrs. Hampton once worked as the treasurer of an Ensign campaign.
Ensign contacted several political sponsors to find Mr. Hampton's work and advocated on behalf of them after they had hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them, according to documents and interviews.
As Hampton had recently been an assistant to Ensign, he was excluded under the law to lobby for his former employer or the Senate for a year.
Ethics experts said that the unusual arrangement between Ensign and Hampton, who were close friends before the affair, appeared in disagreement with the so-called "revolving door lobbying ban", which seeks to restrict former state employees from using their connections to do personal business.
From the evidence that has been made public, "it seemed to be a prima facie case of a conspiracy to substantially violate the revolving door status," said Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in defending clients investigated by the government.
While the officials of the Department of Justice refused to explain the reasoning behind the decision in the Ensign case, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said that the department seemed cautious in accepting political prosecutions after several major setbacks for their public integrity section, including last year's decision to abandon prosecution against former Senator Ted Stevens, in the midst of charges for misconduct of procedure.
Federal prosecutors "are clearly cowards," said Melanie Sloan, Executive Director of Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, a defence group that brought several complaints against Ensign in the case.
"This basically means that high-ranking government officials can now assume that the laws do not apply to them," he added.
Paul Coggins, Ensign's main lawyer, said in an interview that he received a phone call from a prosecutor from the Department of Justice on Monday and another call the next day, telling him that the department did not want to raise charges against his client.
Ensign's defense team had been cooperating with the prosecutors in the attempt to persuade them that the senator, as his office repeated in a statement on Wednesday, "acted in accordance with the law."
Coggins refused to explain in detail the legal arguments he gave to the prosecutors.
"I'm not comfortable getting into details about my discussions with the Department of Justice, I can only say that we thought they made the right decision," he said.
Last month, the Federal Elections Commission decided to change an investigation into a complaint separated by the ethics group, which claims that a payment of $96,000 from Ensign's parents to the Hamptons violated the federal electoral law.
The election commission said it had no proof enough to prove that money was nothing but a gift.
NV Energy is an important company in Nevada that had long supported the senator, which obtained work through lobby thanks to Ensign's help to Hampton.
An e-mail sent in December 2008 showed that after the company accepted Hampton as a lobbist, Ensign's chief of cabinet John Lopez contacted Hampton and told him that he was "matching" the Ministry of the Interior on a disputed issue.
Ensign also attended a lunch with Hampton and another client from Nevada, Allegiant Air, and called on the transport secretary to set up a meeting on behalf of the airline after he had hired Hampton to lobby.
When the news of the affair first appeared last year, Ensign apologized to his voters and gave up his position as fourth Republican leader in the Senate.
After keeping a low profile for many months, two weeks ago Ensign told the journalists that he planned to run for a third term in the Senate.
When Ensign's spokesman Jennifer Cooper announced that Ensign was no longer the subject of a criminal investigation, he said the senator hoped that the ethics committee would quickly follow the example of the Department of Justice and conclude his investigation.
" Senator Ensign is eager to continue his hard work on behalf of the people of Nevada," he said.
