In the end, the defense says, there were over 140,000 Twitter messages about the process that addressed the rape and children tied to their beds in a house that was set on fire.
On Thursday, the widely followed trial of Steven J. Hayes, who was convicted of the murder of three members of a Cheshire family, Connecticut, is ready to reach an official end, with the imposition of the death penalty judge voted by the jury.
But Mr. Hayes' lawyers have submitted written documents to the court that outline the arguments of appeals that will probably occupy the courts for years.
One of the most provocative claims that the intense reports on the process, including the widespread use of Twitter by journalists of mass media, created "a circus atmosphere", and such widespread and immediate saturation with exalting details made public passions exercise inappropriate influence on the jury.
The claim could force appeal judges to deal with the question of whether new technology requires new rules in the courtroom.
