Defence lawyers say they will also question the constitutionality of the death penalty and argue that the judge wrongly removed a jury who had criticized the prosecutors, and that he had incorrectly pressed for a verdict for his strange decision to order the jury to deliberate for a weekend.
The jury wasn't kidnapped.
But your arguments about the effect of the intense coverage of the process can attract most of the interest.
They observed in a challenge to the verdict filed last month that the case dominated the news in Connecticut and was discussed during the electoral campaign by candidates for governor and the United States Senate.
They argued that the media were continually firing fire from emotion on the case.
"The daily agglomeration of media tweets, cameras and reporters outside the court," the lawyers wrote, "was something never seen here in New Haven and perhaps throughout the state."
Your attention to the Tweeter coverage is controversial.
In some interviews, some journalists said that the complaint about the fact that immediate news was more important than the reports delivered more slowly, was a ludita vision that would make the court's policy on coverage control weak in future processes.
But some lawyers said that the appellate courts were often attracted by the adjustment arguments required in the courts due to social and technological changes.
Hayes' lawyers are pressuring for that claim.
In their writing, they referred to the decision of the Supreme Court of 1966, which revoked Dr. Sheppard's conviction due to the coverage of the process, and made it clear that they would require new means to require new rules.
"This case," they wrote, "represents the Sheppard vs. Maxwell case of the 21st century."
Can civicism set up a bridge to unite the divisions?
After a remarkable campaign for invective and negativity, this week has triggered a little civicism in Washington.
Is it a presagio of genuine future bipartisan cooperation or an illusory moment before a quick return to partisan combat in the capital?
The Tuesday meeting between President Obama and Congress leaders did not produce any progress on the major issues to be dealt with during the outgoing session.
But as everyone says, it was at least a polite discussion of the differences of the two sides, as well as an acknowledgement of their shared responsibilities to govern, instead of being another empty episode to win partisan points.
The public meeting on Wednesday of the President's deficit commission was equally civilized, despite the political differences between the members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months generated mutual respect that goes beyond the ideological gap that still separates members.
That is hardly enough to state that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Now both sides are in a trial period, surveying each other to identify signs of cooperativeism and commitment, while trying to evaluate the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters for a renewed partisan war.
A reason why the Tuesday meeting and subsequent evaluations of the meeting by the participants were made with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too large and deeply rooted to suggest any rapid change in the climate that existed over the past two years.
Whether it is tax, expenditure, health care or social assistance, the two sides are in opposite poles.
Anyway, the November election has softened the mood in Washington, at least in the short term.
"There is no doubt that things have changed with regard to how to say things," said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now at the Centre for Ethics and Public Policy.
"They are inevitable after the elections.
The elections raise supportive passions, which are then extinct.
That's good."
On some issues, in particular those on the agenda of the outgoing meeting, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush's tax cuts are over at the end of the year, and nobody is in favour of this.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve some or all reductions, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, there is likely to be a commitment to expand unemployment subsidies, probably because Republicans cannot believe they are in favour of tax reductions for the rich, denying unemployment allowance for unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting in the White House, there is greater optimism for possible treatment of these issues during the outgoing session, along with the ratification of the new START Nuclear Disarmament Pact (Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty).
But William Galston, of the Brookings Institution, warns that successful cooperation on the pressing issues of the outgoing session will not necessarily lead to continued bipartisanism when the new 112th Congress meets in January.
He claimed, on the contrary, that it is very likely and even inevitable that a period of disagreement will begin.
"After the things to be done are carried out, in the short term psychology will reverse the situation to a confrontation," he said.
Wehner also expressed skepticism (which is widely shared) about the fact that civicism can lead to true cooperation.
"I see most of what will happen between now and 2012 as an essay for the 2012 main event," he said.
The reasons have much to do with the constitution of the new Republican majority in the House and the voters of the Tea Party, which contributed decisively to its creation.
As much as the Republican leaders are aware of the dangers of exaggerating their position, they know that they must try to fulfil their promises to cut state spending and override the new health law.
These support lines are already clearly observed in the initial responses to the recommendations of the deficit commission, including the reform of the tax code and the increase of some taxes and retirement age, and the cut in expenditure.
Co-chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have handled one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and, according to their own assessment, have forced the issue of deficit on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes on the 18-member committee to publish their plan as an official recommendation, and they have been struggling to get close to that figure.
The greatest resistance is among the officers elected on the panel, suggesting that there are, at least now, few foundations or desires for commitment in tax matters.
Galston predicts two stages in the battles between the Republicans of the White House and those of Congress.
The first one will happen next year in the form of supportive shocks, when Republicans challenge Obama on the budget, taxes and medical assistance, followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would cause change?
The public opinion.
There is considerable evidence that, despite the partyism of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If the confrontation leads to a deadlock, as happened in 1995, then both parties will carefully observe the reaction of the people.
Whoever they think is losing will probably change course and seek commitment.
However, this can be an optimistic vision.
Partisanism and polarization are now greater than they were in the middle of the 1990s, and there seems to be a larger ideological gap between Obama and Republicans of the Congress that was between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans at the time.
At the same time, the activists of both parties see 2010 as the mere prelude to a more important election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civilism shown this week can be welcomed by many Americans.
But this will require much more effort on both sides to find common points in the issues that still divide them.
A leaked American document portrays Moscow as the paradise of corruption
The city's control is in the hands of a "cleptocracy," and leaves a portion of the bribes and protection money that he collects directly from Kremlin, as reported in February by the US Embassy in Russia.
It was reported that both the police and the Federal Security Service handle huge blackmail systems, which helps explain the high cost of life in Moscow.
They collect money not only from legitimate business, but also from organized criminal groups.
Each stratum of the bureaucracy, which Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has called "vertical authority", takes its part as the money goes up on the scale.
The note, which was sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was published by WikiLeaks on his website on Wednesday.
The note is based on sources whose names have been censored.
It was written while Yuri Luzhkov was still mayor of Moscow, and blamed him for much of corruption.
President Dmitry Medvedev fired him in October, but there has been little evidence of cleaning since then.
Luzhkov and his wife, Yelena Baturina, who owns an important construction company, have consistently denied allegations of corruption over the years, and he has won several claims for release on such accusations.
In September, when on a Russian television channel he was asked about a documentary that suggested that he was corrupt, he said: "It's madness, a scam, a mess."
According to surveys, Russians overwhelmingly believe that their society is corrupt.
But it is unusual to find details explained in detail, as they were in the embassy's report, and it is unheard that it is the diplomats of a foreign country who do that.
"The direct links of the Moscow city government with criminality have led some to call it 'disfunctional', and to claim that the government works more as a cleptocrat than a government," the note states.
"The criminal elements enjoy a 'krysha' (a term of the criminal world and the mafia that literally means "weather" or protection) passed by the police, the Federal Security Service (SFS), the Ministry of Internal Affairs (MVD), and the prosecutor's office, as well as all sectors of the government bureaucracy of the city of Moscow.
"The analysts identify a three-level structure in the criminal world of Moscow."
"Luzhkov is at the highest."
"SFS, MVD and militia are on second level."
"Finally, common criminals and corrupt inspectors are at the lowest level."
"This is an ineffective system in which criminal groups fill a vacuum in some areas, because the city does not provide some services."
The report states that the SFS raises the money from larger companies, and that the police point to small businesses.
One source, said the report, "explained that the commercial owners of Moscow understand that the best thing is to get protection from MVD and SFS (instead of organized crime groups) as they not only have more weapons, resources and power than criminal groups, but are also protected by law."
"For this reason, protection against criminal gangs is no longer a priority."
The note notes that while the collection of money is complete, protection may be irregular; even those who pay are subject to arrest.
Those who do not pay quickly find their business closed by one pretext or another.
Medvedev has spoken several times about the fight against corruption, but has confessed that he has made little progress.
The embassy note reports about men taking suitcases, probably full of cash, inside Kremlin himself.
"In his fight against corruption, Medvedev has to trust the bureaucrats," said Georgy Satarov, director of the Indem expert group in Moscow, in a recent interview.
"But he's a part of this bureaucracy."
"He does not belong to a political class, because there is no longer a political class in Russia."
Without politics, without opposition, without separation of powers, he said, corruption is inevitable.
At the national level, Indem estimates that corruption costs Russia more than $300 billion a year.
In a recent survey of global perceptions of corruption carried out by the non-governmental organization Transparency International, the country was ranked 154 (the countries are classified from less to the most corrupt).
The revelation of the American Embassy's note, which did not happen until late at night Moscow hour, will probably cause disgust within the Russian government, and despite the fact that Luzhkov can be blamed for Moscow's weaknesses, it could be an opportunity for the Kremlin to argue that it is solving the problem.
Interviewed for the CNN by Larry King, Putin suggested that WikiLeaks documents could be lies and reacted furiously by a revelation that claimed that American diplomats called him Batman and Medvedev Robin.
"The truth of the matter is that this is related to our interaction, which is an important factor in domestic policies in this country," he said.
"But to be honest with you, we do not suspect that this would have been done with such arrogance, with such pressure and, you know, that it was done in such an immoral way."
The veterans of the Red Jemeres forced to face the past
In a specific classroom, weakly illuminated, with stained and outdated walls, the director of the Anlong Veng Secondary School reminded the man who had built it, the last leader of the Ta Mok Red Jemeres.
"Everyone here loves Ta Mok."
"He was a good leader and worried about his people," said 42-year-old Sreng Kor Ma.
Known as "the butcher" for his brutality during the government of the Red Jemeres, the commander remains popular in this remote former fortress of the Red Jemeres in northwest Cambodia, where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructures, and where thousands of former soldiers of the organization still live.
But this year, 12 years after the Red Jemeres surrendered to the government, long lasting loyalty is finally being challenged in Anlong Veng.
In April, a local forum for truth and reconciliation allowed victims to face publicly those who had participated in the regime.
In June, the government distributed here a secondary school textbook that for the first time teaches the history of the Red Jemeres to the children of their former soldiers.
And in July, a joint United Nations and Cambodia court issued the first sentence of a former member of the Red Jemers, condemning the former head of the known torture center Tuol Sleng, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as Duch, to 35 years in prison.
With each of these events, anxiety has grown among the veterans of the Anlong Veng Red Jemeres, complicating efforts for reconciliation and their attempts to reintegrate into Cambodian society.
"There is resentment and fear among the former Red Jemeres, but they can't do anything," said Chhang Youk, director of the Cambodia Documentation Center, an independent organization that investigates the regime.
"For them, life under the Red Jemeres was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil."
"This is generating divisions within families."
During the government of the Cambodian Red Jemeres, between 1975 and 1979, some 1.7 million people were executed or died of hunger, disease or overwork.
When in 1979 the Vietnamese invaded and overthrown the government led by Pol Pot, the remnants of the regime and their military fled to the Cambodian border with Thailand.
There they launched an insurrection that lasted until the last movement that gave up in December 1998.
Like Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary led the guerrilla war from their bases in the mountains and jungles of Western Cambodia, Ta Mok cultivated followers in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a UN-sponsored peace agreement led to the country's first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of combatants of the Red Jemers began to desert towards the government, culminating in the renditions of Ieng Sary in 1996, and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998, and Ta Mok, who had resisted, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the nearby Dangrek Mountains.
He died in a Phnom Penh prison in 2006 while waiting for the trial.
Without the support of their benefactors, the oldest fighters of the Red Jemeres fell into the absolute misery that is common in rural Cambodia, and many feel nostalgia for the movement.
Although a few Red Jemeres elite officials retained their local administrative positions in exchange for depopulating their weapons, standard soldiers remain poor and unskilled farmers.
"These people have obtained few benefits after surrender," said Sok Leang of the Justice and Reconciliation Center, which offers public forums throughout Cambodia, even in Anlong Veng.
"They have incorporated the utopian agricultural ideology of the regime."
"They were raised without any concept to do business."
Sor Lim, 55, who joined the Red Jemeres when he was a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle near Anlong Veng before dedicating himself to life as a poor rice farmer in 1998.
"Life with the Red Jemeres was fine," he said.
"Ta Mok gave everyone food."
"But now life is difficult because we have to supply ourselves."
The current Red Jemers court has also caused concerns here.
At the beginning of next year, the court is expected to begin to prosecute Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former Minister of the Red Jemers.
The mandate of the court is to prosecute the principal leaders and those who are most responsible for the crimes, but he has not said whether he will pursue cases in addition to those four.
This didn't do much to calm the fears at Anlong Veng.
The recent media speculation has focused on 64-year-old Im Chaem, who was a district chief in the province of Banteay Meanchey during the government of the Red Jemeres in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told the researchers at the Cambodia Documentation Centre that she had supervised the construction of the Trapeang Thma dam, a project in which thousands of forced workers are thought to have died.
During a recent embarrassing afternoon, Im Chaem returned from working in the fields to his home on wooden pilots on a land road on the outskirts of Anlong Veng.
When the sun threw long shadows on the dry grass, Im Chaem refused to talk about his past in the Red Jemeres.
She claimed that if the court had convened it, it would not be presented.
"Cambodia is in peace and stability," he said.
"If there are more prosecutions, there will be war."
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who deserted the Red Jemeres in 1978, has also repeatedly warned that there will be instability if the court pursues more suspects, although experts and historians question it.
"Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past," he said.
But facing the past is just what Cambodia must do to move forward, said Chhang Youk, from the documentation center.
"Reconciliation, according to Khmer, is to rejoin the broken pieces," he said.
"It is our obligation to gather these broken pieces so that we can understand."
The center produced the first textbook approved by the government on the Red Jemeres, called "A History of Democratic Kampuchea", of 75 pages.
It was distributed in Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the secondary school history textbook of the Ministry of Education, which contains less than four pages on the Red Jemeres.
As in most Cambodia, young people from Anlong Veng know few details about the Red Jemeres, despite the link of the city to the regime.
Toque Valeak, 19, a student at Anlong Veng Secondary School, said that the new textbook helped students understand an important part of their history.
But his parents reacted with skepticism when he took the book home to study.
"My family rejects many parts of the textbook and the court," he said.
"They have suspicions because they are not sure how many people the court will prosecute."
Such resistance has made the reconciliation process complex and difficult, Sok Leang said.
But public forums, the textbook and the court are beginning to produce an impact, he said.
Anyway, here the Red Jemers preserve a powerful charm.
In the Dangrek Mountains, a road with too many weeds and covered with discarded plastic bags leads to a rectangle of the black hollin covered by a oxidized roof of leafboard.
Pol Pot's body was burned here on a lot of tyres after his death in 1998.
Nuom Sothea, 31, a cell salesman at the edge of the road, said he didn't know much about the man who was cremated there.
"But he has a strong spirit and many inhabitants of the place go there to pray," he said.
It was Nuom Sothea's birthday, and later that day he decided to walk to the place of Pol Pot's last rest, where he would leave a bunch of mature bananas in the hope of having good luck.
Belarus agrees to renounce its arms-qualified uranium reserve
In a surprising victory for President Obama's campaign to protect nuclear material around the world, the Belarusian government announced Wednesday that it will renounce its highly enriched uranium reserve, a critical component of nuclear weapons.
The treatment was revealed in a joint statement published after Foreign Minister Hillary Rodham Clinton met with Belarusian Foreign Minister Sergei Martynov, outside a security summit.
For years, the U.S. government had been trying to persuade Belarus to give up its highly enriched uranium and seemed to have reached a point without return last spring.
But U.S. officials told Washington Post that a couple of operations classified with Belarus were carried out in the last two months to remove 84.82 kg of qualified uranium for weapons from a Belarusian research facility.
This prepared the ground for Wednesday's agreement to remove the rest of the material, approximately 227 kg, according to an official, who spoke from anonymity due to the confidentiality of the subject.
The agreement seemed to be one of the most important results of the 47-nation Nuclear Security Summit chaired by Obama in April, which excluded Belarus.
And it was apparently a good achievement to ensure the invitation of the former Soviet Republic to the next summit in 2012.
"I was really fascinated by the fact that they wanted a place at the 2012 Nuclear Security Summit."
"This shows that this process is working," said Ken Luongo, president of the Society for Global Security, a group that promotes nuclear safety.
Clinton said the agreement is "a very significant and important step" by Belarus.
In April 2009, Obama promised in Prague to protect all vulnerable nuclear material worldwide in the next four years.
Since then, the U.S. government has helped six countries get rid of all their highly enriched uranium.
Belarus would be the seventh.
A dozen countries did so under George W. Bush's administration.
At the time of the Obama Nuclear Security Summit, the Belarusian President, Alexander Lukashenko, had declared that the nation would never renounce its uranium.
"We have preserved the highly enriched uranium (hundreds of kilograms of what is basically qualified uranium for weapons) and the low-enriched uranium," Lukashenko said at that time.
"This is our raw material... we're not gonna make dirty bombs, and we're not gonna sell them to anyone."
"We use it for research purposes, that's all."
However, Belarus approached the United States a few months ago, indicating an interest in reaching an agreement.
The officials stated that the first task of withdrawing the uranium from Belarus in October was particularly complicated, as the material had been slightly irradiated.
Officials said it was loaded on a special train that travelled over 2,000 km to a Russian storage and disposal facility.
According to officials, the second operation ended on Monday and was made by plane.
The U.S. government spent $13 million on the task, and most of the money was used to provide Belarus with the installation of low-enrichment uranium research, which is not suitable for nuclear weapons.
Andrew Bieniawski, an official of the Department of Energy working on Global Threat Reduction, said that "this was coordinated and orchestrated very carefully to strengthen confidence," which led to the agreement signed by Clinton.
