Sport and law fraud
Treats like those of Alonso and Ramos before the Ajax demonstrate ingenuity but will not escape a sanction.
The expulsion allegedly driven by two players from Real Madrid (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the match contested on November 23 against the Ajax in the Champions League has caused ink rivers to be written about whether such behavior is unsportable or not and whether, eventually, both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, in the absence of a few minutes to finish the game (which your team had already clearly won), the two players deliberately lost time in making mistakes to cause the arbitrator to show them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid will end up as the leader of its group, both players will comply with the regulatory sanction the next match of the liguilla, against the Auxerre, and they will be able to pass clean cards to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee has sanctioned the team's coach, José Mourinho, with two matches, and with various economic amounts to the players involved.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, but rather frequent in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, of the unwritten but followed rules of this sport.
Part of the discussion that emerged in the reported case is because it has been starred by a team of the entity of Real Madrid (which in its anthem presume of nobility and honor, and which on past occasion has fined its players for similar acts) and the dramatization orchestrated, apparently, by Mourinho, who adds one more episode to his extended history of histrionic and provocative technician.
In any event, the debate focuses on whether such behaviour not expressly prohibited by the regulation contradicts the principles of sport, i.e. whether these actions are committed by law fraud; since they are indeed actions respectful of the sport regulations, but they seem to circumvent their meaning.
The issue goes on to examine the type of damage they cause to the sporting spirit.
One of the goods that understands the sporting spirit is the physical integrity of the opposite players, an aspect that with these actions did not jeopardize, that is, there was no violent game.
Another of these goods that you refer to with the clean game is to prevent the team of offenders from taking advantage unfairly of the opposing team, which didn't happen either.
Now, the paradoxical of the action of Real Madrid players is that it did not fit into what we normally characterize as a trap or fraud of law, because its violation of the rules was not hid to try to avoid the sanction, but precisely its action tried to be the most evident to receive the punishment of the arbitrator.
They gladly waited and accepted the penalty.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders obtain in the intentional misdemeanours examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that the rival is not disadvantaged or profitable in the same party, since obviously the result of the action means leaving the team itself with fewer players.
And it's also not a useful strategy for the next match, as the club will not be able to count on those players.
The advantage, obviously, is that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that can threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indetermination, as the team can be eliminated to the first change, and in addition with this performance the players meet a penalty match and move to the second cycle of cards, in which the card accumulation suspension occurs with one less than in the first cycle.
So, going rounds, it's not so clear that it's an advantage.
In short, these actions are not against the sporting spirit, of which it is part to make strategic decisions that favour making the most of what the rules allow.
In the case we are concerned, the players did not act to evade the application of the penalty (this would be a clear case of law fraud), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without redressing the punishment or fleeing it.
Although the border between ingenuity and law fraud is diffuse, on this occasion I think it was a clear case of ingenuity.
The controversy, I think, arises from two factors: because it was two self-expulsions and the way in which the directive was transmitted to cause them.
The damage caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not as ethical as it is aesthetic.
