EU changes rules for obtaining visa
People should go to Visa applicant Service centres prior to their interview in the Consular Section; the cost will be lower and the waiting time.
As of 10 January 2011, it will change the procedure for processing a visa at the U.S. Embassy and consulates.
With the new procedure, most applicants will have to go to Visa Applicants Service Centres (ASCs) prior to their interview with the Consular Section.
ASC staff shall take the applicant's biometric information, which shall be reviewed by the Consular Section before the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for applicants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, it will no longer be necessary to make a payment to conclude the appointment, another payment to process the visa application and another one for the messaging service to deliver the document.
The applicant will only make a single payment covering the three services.
The current rate will remain unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa cases on request (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for traders and investors visas.
Persons wishing to renew their visa will not have to attend an interview with the Consular Officer, but will only go to the nearest ASC where they will submit their documents and take their prints.
Because the biometric information will be taken in the ASC, applicants who require a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will remain in this less time than in the past.
Similarly, those who apply for a visa at the Consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the $26 extra service fee.
For further information on the new visa application procedure, visit the following page: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
