A Global Plan to Renew Lighting
Yesterday, the UN has proposed in Cancún a plan for the renewal of domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in a hundred countries to reduce greenhouse gases (GHGs) by a quantity that corresponds to almost one third of the additional decrease to be made to stabilize the planet's climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is part of the set of major concrete projects that the UN hopes will be adopted in Cancún to offset the lack of binding reduction commitments in industrialized countries.
According to the plan submitted yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs, which still monopolize between 50 and 70% of the market, were replaced by fluocompact bulbs or, even better, by electroluminescent diodes bulbs (DEL or "LED" in English), much of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of GHG issued on the planet would be avoided to illuminate humans.
Lighting is responsible for 8 per cent of global emissions.
It is the equivalent of 70% of the emissions of the planetary car park.
In Copenhagen last year, large emitting countries, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed themselves to voluntary reduction plans that should reduce global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, 5 Gt of that quantity should be further reduced to stabilize by 2020 the increase in temperatures in two degrees centigrade to avoid decontrol.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of energy dissipates in the form of heat and the rest, i.e. 5%, produces light.
In the case of fluocompact bulbs, energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with new LED bulbs, energy consumption is reduced twice as much.
Fluocompact bulbs last an average of between 6,000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those launched by manufacturer Philips this week (a company that has also participated in the UN study), have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, allowing us to make an idea of the savings that can be achieved with the replacement plan that would be implemented in a hundred countries.
These new bulbs can also work with rheostats and emit very little heat.
Above, they don't contain any mercury.
Various specialists have expressed their reservations regarding fluocompact bulbs, since they contain mercury and must be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless manufacturers place instructions.
However, the report indicates that the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not fluocompact bulbs, but coal thermal power plants, which emit a large amount of mercury to produce electricity that is wasted by incandescent bulbs.
Only in the United States, these plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report details the advantages that this international programme would offer to each country.
For example, Indonesia would thus save $1 billion a year in electricity and $8 million in tons of CO2, i.e. the equivalent of 3.5 thermal plants whose construction would cost $2.5 billion.
