Avenger hackers and diligent spies
The WikiLeaks case has a double value.
On the one hand, it reveals an apparent scandal, a scandal that only seems scandalous in the face of hypocrisy that governs relations between States, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes at the international level and envisages a future dominated by regression.
But let's go step by step.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that each file created by a secret service (regardless of the nation to which it belongs) is made up exclusively of press cuts.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual customs only reflect what has been written for months in any newspaper (except those belonging to Berlusconi) and Khadafi's sinisterly ridiculing profile has long been giving cabaret artists ideas to create their sketches.
The rule that secret files should only be made up of news of public knowledge is essential for the dynamics of secret services, and not only in this century.
If you visit a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats (on the Grial, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rosacruz) exactly what had been written in the previous works.
This is not only because the authors of occult texts do not want to do unpublished investigations (or do not know where to look for news about the nonexistent), but because those who dedicate themselves to occultism not only trust what they already know, which reconfirms what they had already learned.
This is Dan Brown's success mechanism.
The same applies to secret files.
The informant is lazy, just as he is lazy (or has little desire) the head of secret services (if it couldn't be, I know, editor of Liberation), who only considers true what he can recognize.
The top secret information about Berlusconi sent by the American Embassy of Rome to the Department of State was the same as the Newsweek published last week.
So why have the revelations of these files caused such a revolt?
On the one hand, they only say what every grown person already knows, that is, that the embassies, at least since World War II and since the heads of State can call on the phone or catch the plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic role and, with the exception of some limited representation exercises, have become spy centers.
Any viewer who sees research films knows perfectly, we just seem to know that we don't know it for hypocrisy.
In any case, the fact of repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy and gives a bad picture of American diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can consult the most secret secrets of the world's most powerful country significantly affects the prestige of the Department of State.
Therefore, the scandal affects both the victims and the "punishers".
But let us enter the true nature of what has happened.
Formerly, in the Orwell era, it could be conceived of all power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell's prophecy has come true since, being able to control every movement thanks to the phone, every transaction made, visited hotel, taken highway, the citizen thus became a complete victim of the eye of power.
But when it is shown, as it is now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, chosen as the avenger of the citizens) can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that can no longer hold its own secrets?
It is true, as Georg Simmel already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that any knowledge of the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is actually an empty secret, without secret, since it comes from the public sphere; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks has done, that Hillary Clinton's secrets were empty secrets means to take away all power from him.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but yes, and much, to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound caused to such a powerful power?
It is clear that, in the future, States will no longer be able to put any reserved information on the network, as it would be like publishing it on a poster on the street.
But it is also clear that, with current technologies, confidential conversations cannot be expected on the phone.
Nothing is easier than to find out if and when a Head of State has travelled by plane and has contacted one of the counterparts.
How can they maintain private and confidential relations in the future?
I know perfectly well that, for the time being, my prediction is a matter of science fiction and, therefore, novelistic, but I imagine government agents who move discreetly in diligence with uncontrollable itineraries, carrying messages that have been learned from memory or, at the very least, hiding some data written in the heels of their shoes.
This information is then kept, in one copy, in closed drawers with keys: in the end, the attempted espionage of the Watergate was less successful than WikiLeaks.
In the past, I have written that technology is currently progressing as a crab, i.e. backwards.
A century after the cableless telegraph has revolutionized communications, the Internet has re-created a cable (telephonic) telegraph.
Video tapes (analogs) had allowed film researchers to study a movie step by step, moving forward and backwards, discovering all the secrets of assembly, while now CDs (digital) only allow progress or backwards from chapter to chapter, i.e. to huge proportions.
With the high-speed trains, we can go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, with the travels it carries, we need three and a half hours.
Therefore, it is nothing out of the ordinary that politics and communication techniques will take us back to horse cars.
One last comment.
Formerly, the press tried to understand what was secretly planned in the embassies.
The embassies are currently asking the press for confidential information.
Climate: France's whims in its pledges of financing
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine whether the fast-start or early-start pledges made by developed countries have been respected.
And the French chapuzas have been unveiled.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union undertook to contribute €7.2 billion in three years and €1.260 million in France (i.e. €420 million per year).
During the opening of COP16, the EU has put on the table its best letters to convince its partners that its commitment to fast start funding is true: a report detailing the measures of its Member States, a press conference, a major complementary event, the distribution of brochures...
The transparency operation was appreciable and was appreciated for what it really is worth: developing countries and civil society would want all developed countries to do the same and with the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released EUR 2.2 billion in 2010, which puts it on the right track towards fulfilling its commitment of EUR 7.2 billion in 2012.
But if we study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Agreement, money must be "new and additional" to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without prejudice to official development aid.
Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached on what "new and additional" means.
When the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the procedure.
At present, each of them chooses the reference that is best suited to it.
For example, the European Commission has made reference to 2009: international funding is maintained and 150 million in three years are added for fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references for the year or level of official development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers that the financing of "all new projects" for 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, no reference is made to the expenditures of previous years or to the total level of official development aid.
In particular, France's total aid to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), while it intends to respect its commitment to "new and additional" funds...
Another crucial element, the distribution between donations and loans.
Once again, there is no standard and each chooses the method of calculation.
Some, like France, consider that each euro borrowed is equivalent to a donated euro.
Obviously, such a thing is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain investments that are profitable (frequently, projects related to emission reduction based on more efficient technologies), it is impossible to present a euro that is to be recovered as an equivalent to a donated euro... At the very least, only the cost of the loan to the loan country should be calculated for its commitments (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France finds no such reasoning useful: "respects" its commitment of EUR 420 million by making 91.5% of loans (389.8 million) and 8.5% of donations (EUR 36.1 million); see the EU document to see it in its own eyes.
This is the only country in the Union that uses the loan so often.
Germany uses it at 46 per cent, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia, among others, respects their commitments to 100 per cent grants.
In other words, when most of the European Union provides a euro to fulfil its commitment, France only provides ten cents and considers the effort to be comparable.
A good trick!
In short, in its fast start financing, France is doing a double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to actions over time and on the other, in relation to the real financial effort.
Using just 36.1 million euros, he gets the impression that he spends 420 million "new and additional", as he promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems Bercy has dealt with arbitration) could have a two-fold negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to donate when they can simply lend?) and in negotiations, since developing countries are not foolish...
The chapter on early financing is a relatively short-term detail in relation to the whole of the climate negotiations.
But it could be a grain of more sand in the vast machinery that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope it's not like that.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First, France could announce a change in its method of calculation for the years 2011 and 2012, with the intention of respecting its commitments and in the same way as the other countries of the European Union.
But, in particular, France could move forward the discussions on the stakes at stake in relation to long-term financing (another essential chapter that is currently being discussed): we will not get rid of the question of "additional character" or the method of calculating loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on this issue as it is on others.
We therefore have the hope of the new Environment Minister, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancún next week.
A surprise announcement about France's fast start and its vision of the "additional character" and the use of loans would help to improve the level of international confidence needed to advance the negotiations.
Warning on pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old eats in a day 81 different chemicals, according to a study published on Wednesday by the association Générations Futures (the old movement for the rights and respect of future generations).
The association, which warns that its results "do not have a significant statistical value taking into account the limited number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem addressed," acquired in supermarkets in Oise and Paris between July and September the foods that a child of about ten years consumes in four meals and a tentempié a day.
These meals taken as a model, which respect the official recommendations (five parts of fresh fruit and vegetables, three of dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day), as well as candy, were examined in the laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The balance of the dish is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 classified as potential or likely cancers and five substances classified as safe cancers, as well as 37 substances susceptible to acting as endocrine disturbers (EP), according to studies by various institutions such as the International Research Centre on Cancer.
"Although, in virtually all cases, the legal limits for each of the chemicals are not exceeded individually, our study clearly shows that exposure of consumers to potentially canceric pollutants and/or PE is worrying," the association points out.
For breakfast, butter and tea with milk alone contain more than a dozen possible cancer residues and three considered safe cancers, as well as about 20 residues that may harm the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, foreseen as a bakery for school, contains traces of six chemical substances, including a fungicid prohibited in France.
The same applies to Kenyan green beans, including food, where the study has detected traces of a powerful insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, Russian steak, canned tuna and even the bread bar or gum were fed with pesticides and other chemicals.
In the tap water, the analyses discovered the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon slice was the most "nutritive" with 34 chemical residues detected and even the analysis of the plastic dish used to heat the food in the microwave was not completely clean.
The final risk generated by these "polluter cocktails" for the consumer is "probably underestimated," the study says.
The Europe Ecology-Les Verts Alliance (EE-LV), for its part, has proposed "to deal with the seriousness of the situation" to apply a moratorium on the use of pesticides to curb "the increase in diseases associated with civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EASA) indicated the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, of which 76 in cereals.
